The collections contain 6 impressions os cordate-orbicular leaves which differ only in an additional pair of secondaries along the midrib from the type and figured specimen of Menisper- mites kniqhtz'i. The original description was as follows:

“Leas evidently thick in texture, broadly cordate, with roundcd base and very deep sinuses‚ rounded, truncate at apex ; margin undulate lobed, the lobes very short, obtuse, and entire or erose; nervation palmate, with about seven primary nerves os equal strength which apparently pass to the rounded lobes or are once or twice forked, the branches passing to the lobes; finer

nervation not preserved.'’

The observable characters of this leaf form resemble those of several menispermaceous genera, particularly Caeculus. On the other hand, the thick texture is suggestive of an aquatic leaf. Among aquatic genera there is a marked resemblance to several of the Nymphaeaceae, particularly Castalia (Nymphaea). These differ, however, in minor respects, mainly in their more numerous secondaries and in their deeply cordate bases. In the absence of better comparison with modern leaves, it seems advisable to retain the more general name applied by Knowlton.

This species is at present known only from the Lance formation and the Mesaverde formation os southeastern Wyoming.

Occurrence—Locality P3858.

Collection—U. C. Mus. Pal., Plesiotype No. 2521.

Family MAGNOLIACEAE

Genus MAGNOLIOPHYLLUM Conwentz Magnoliophyllum cordatum Dorf

Maqnoliophyllmn cordatum Dorf, Farnegie Inst.. Wash. Pub. No. 508, pt. 1, 64, pl. 9, fig. 5, pl. 10, fig. l, 193& Bull. Geol. Soc. Amen, vol. 51, 218, 222, 225, 1940,

This species is not abundant in the collections. Only 4 specimens of incomplete, though well-preserved, leaves were encountered. The general shape‚ the cordate base, and the prominent secondaries with pronounced marginal loops are sufficiently well shown, however, to permit the determination without hesitation.

I have not as yet encountered specimcns or figures of previously reported leaves of this form in the Cretaceous or early Tertiary floras, aside from those of the Medicine Bow flora. The re- semblance of these forms to the leaves of the Magnoliaceae has already been discussed in the original description of this species.

Occurrence—Localities P3855, P3857.

Collection—U. C. Mus. Pal., No. 2522.
